MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon to everybody

00:00:03.930 --> 00:00:04.846
here in Mountain View.

00:00:04.846 --> 00:00:05.790
Thanks for coming out.

00:00:05.790 --> 00:00:08.970
And to our Googlers tuning in
at offices around the world,

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:09.470
hello.

00:00:09.470 --> 00:00:11.180
Good day to you as well.

00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:13.170
We have a really exciting
hour ahead of us.

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:15.630
We're here with Ashlee
Vance, as you guys know.

00:00:15.630 --> 00:00:18.492
So Ashlee's a
featured journalist

00:00:18.492 --> 00:00:19.700
for Bloomberg "Businessweek."

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:21.158
He's written a
bunch-- I think over

00:00:21.158 --> 00:00:24.130
a dozen now-- feature and
cover stories for Bloomberg.

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:26.197
And we're here today to
talk about his new book.

00:00:26.197 --> 00:00:27.280
I think it was out in May?

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:27.810
ASHLEE VANCE: Yep.

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:28.518
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:00:28.518 --> 00:00:29.950
It's "Elon Musk."

00:00:29.950 --> 00:00:32.680
And so you call yourself-- you
can call yourself an Elon Musk

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:34.140
biographer now.

00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:35.500
Very exciting stuff.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:37.990
And is the book-- I think I
read it's a "New York Times"

00:00:37.990 --> 00:00:38.700
bestseller now?

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:40.170
ASHLEE VANCE: It's been
on the bestseller list

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:41.796
just about since it
came out, 12 weeks.

00:00:41.796 --> 00:00:42.795
MALE SPEAKER: Very cool.

00:00:42.795 --> 00:00:43.550
Congratulations.

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:44.520
And its rightfully so.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:45.660
It's a fascinating read.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:47.110
If you haven't
checked it out yet,

00:00:47.110 --> 00:00:49.500
I highly encourage you to do so.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:52.510
So we've got about 30 or 40
minutes of facilitated Q&amp;A

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:53.654
we're going to do.

00:00:53.654 --> 00:00:55.070
And then we have
a mic in the back

00:00:55.070 --> 00:00:58.760
to pass around for audience
question-and-answer as well.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:02.850
So to begin, so Ashlee,
before Bloomberg, you

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:05.760
were with "New York Times," "The
Economist," a few other places.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.580
How'd you get into
tech journalism?

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:09.220
And specifically,
how did you decide

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:10.990
to write a book about Elon?

00:01:10.990 --> 00:01:13.615
ASHLEE VANCE: Well, I guess it's
sorts of two different things.

00:01:13.615 --> 00:01:16.000
I mean, I kind of stumbled
into tech journalism.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.140
I was a philosophy
major at college.

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:20.700
So I had to find a
way to feed myself.

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:23.249
And I had always
wanted to be a writer,

00:01:23.249 --> 00:01:25.290
but I'd never really
thought of being a reporter.

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:28.702
And I had graduated
during the dot-com boom.

00:01:28.702 --> 00:01:30.150
And there were tons of jobs.

00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:31.650
I wanted to live
in San Francisco.

00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:34.610
And there were tons
of reporter jobs

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:38.840
open for anyone who wanted to be
paid very little and work hard.

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:39.890
So I did that.

00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:41.220
And I ended up liking it.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:44.800
I got thrown into covering
semiconductors and networking

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:45.300
equipment.

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:47.610
I was working for a trade
publication, basically,

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:49.767
and knew nothing about
any of the stuff.

00:01:49.767 --> 00:01:54.920
So I downloaded Unix, started
learning about RISC chips,

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:58.220
and then off I went.

00:01:58.220 --> 00:01:59.880
The Elon thing, I
mean, I guess it

00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:03.560
does sort of come out
from that a little bit.

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:07.480
I was never the person that
covered consumer tech stuff

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:11.734
and was never like
really into the-- I mean,

00:02:11.734 --> 00:02:13.150
I was into the
web, but not-- it's

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:15.316
just never the area that I
really wrote about a lot.

00:02:15.316 --> 00:02:18.790
I always wrote about companies
that actually made things

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:19.900
and that had factories.

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:21.050
And I don't know why.

00:02:21.050 --> 00:02:23.760
That's just kind of when
I gravitated towards.

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:28.879
And so I was not like that
into Elon until about 2012

00:02:28.879 --> 00:02:30.170
and I did a cover story on him.

00:02:30.170 --> 00:02:33.780
And when I saw Tesla's
factories and SpaceX factories--

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.412
especially SpaceX-- I decided
that's what I had to do.

00:02:36.412 --> 00:02:37.120
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:37.690
Fair enough.

00:02:37.690 --> 00:02:40.420
So was Elon on board
from the beginning?

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:42.370
How did that go?

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:45.270
ASHLEE VANCE: So in 2012, I did
a "Businessweek" cover story

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:47.140
on Elon.

00:02:47.140 --> 00:02:50.140
And we got along pretty well.

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:52.776
I got to spend a bunch
of time with him,

00:02:52.776 --> 00:02:54.150
going through the
SpaceX factory.

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.592
We went to movie premieres
and all this stuff.

00:02:56.592 --> 00:03:00.840
And the companies
were very interesting.

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:02.640
And Elon was much
more interesting

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:06.930
than I'd given him credit
for before the story.

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:10.270
I'd sort of pegged him as just
like a one-note techno-utopian

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:10.900
kind of guy.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:13.640
And he turned out to be
this great interview.

00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:16.370
He didn't have PR
handlers around him.

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:17.920
So you had access to him.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:21.300
And he would answer just
about anything you asked him.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:25.732
And so I decided
then, this is a guy

00:03:25.732 --> 00:03:26.940
I really want to write about.

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:28.810
And I'd been looking
for a book to do.

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.880
And so after I did the story,
a couple months went by.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:34.680
And then I started to feel
Elon out about doing a book.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:37.950
And I think I either
sent him an email

00:03:37.950 --> 00:03:40.650
or called him on the phone.

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:42.250
And I said, this is
what I want to do.

00:03:42.250 --> 00:03:43.749
And he said, look,
a bunch of people

00:03:43.749 --> 00:03:47.987
have asked me in the past,
and I'm not going to do it.

00:03:47.987 --> 00:03:49.570
I'm not going to
help you do the book.

00:03:49.570 --> 00:03:54.310
And then I went to New York,
and I sold the book anyway.

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:57.390
And I thought I would sort of
force his hand a little bit.

00:03:57.390 --> 00:03:59.664
And then I arranged
another meeting with him.

00:03:59.664 --> 00:04:00.580
And I'll never forget.

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:02.670
It was on a Saturday at Tesla.

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:03.309
And I came in.

00:04:03.309 --> 00:04:04.850
I was like, look,
I've sold the book.

00:04:04.850 --> 00:04:08.690
And he said, I'm still not
going to cooperate with you.

00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:12.160
And so I spent 18
months interviewing

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:13.010
hundreds of people.

00:04:13.010 --> 00:04:17.670
I found all these SpaceX and
Tesla employees, most of whom

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:18.170
had left.

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:20.779
All the Zip2, Paypal people
that he'd worked with,

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:23.470
his ex-girlfriends,
his childhood friends,

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:24.620
and all that stuff.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:29.020
And then a lot of those
people would call back to Elon

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:30.920
and say, should I
speak to him or not?

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:32.590
And he was a pretty
good sport about it.

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:34.550
There's nobody that
he told not to.

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:36.630
And so I think that
happened enough times

00:04:36.630 --> 00:04:42.120
that after about 18 months
of doing it, I was at home.

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.045
It was like 6:30 at
night on a weekday,

00:04:44.045 --> 00:04:48.110
and up on my caller
ID, it was Elon Musk.

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:49.960
And I picked up the phone.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.199
And he said, look, I
can basically-- this

00:04:53.199 --> 00:04:54.490
is going to go one of two ways.

00:04:54.490 --> 00:04:57.490
I can shut down all
these people that call me

00:04:57.490 --> 00:05:01.020
and ask whether I should
let them talk to you,

00:05:01.020 --> 00:05:03.250
or I could cooperate
with the book.

00:05:03.250 --> 00:05:07.240
I was like, obviously, you
should choose option b.

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:12.305
And then we set up a
meeting to talk about it.

00:05:12.305 --> 00:05:15.420
He wanted to be able
to-- he wanted to have

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:17.540
some control over it initially.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:21.160
He wanted to be able to read
the book before it came out.

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:23.160
And then he wanted to put
footnotes in the book.

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:25.930
And if you know
anything about Elon,

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:29.520
that would mean the footnotes
would be longer than the book

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:32.190
and that the book would
probably never be published.

00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:34.860
And so I kind of pushed
back on him on that.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:36.430
I had this huge speech prepared.

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.730
And I got five minutes into
it, and he just said, OK.

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:43.690
Yeah, to his credit,
after that, he gave me

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:45.220
access to everybody I wanted.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:49.137
And then he agreed to have a
meeting with me once a month,

00:05:49.137 --> 00:05:50.470
he said, for as long as it took.

00:05:50.470 --> 00:05:52.020
It ended up being
about eight months.

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:54.950
And we would have three-,
four-, five-hour dinners.

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:55.700
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:57.908
So the book, I have to say,
especially the beginning,

00:05:57.908 --> 00:05:59.350
it reads like a
suspense thriller,

00:05:59.350 --> 00:06:01.670
even though it's nonfiction
because-- I don't

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:03.936
want to give too much
away, but it opens with you

00:06:03.936 --> 00:06:06.060
kind of showing up a little
early for this meeting,

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:09.140
sitting down with a drink,
waiting for Elon to show up,

00:06:09.140 --> 00:06:12.410
knowing full well that this is
kind of a make-or-break moment.

00:06:12.410 --> 00:06:15.150
And it goes well, like you said.

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:18.740
I can't believe you didn't agree
to his two demands, by the way.

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:20.680
They seemed reasonable, but--

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:22.096
ASHLEE VANCE: There
was part of me

00:06:22.096 --> 00:06:24.340
that-- so Elon's got this
very unique writing style.

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:25.923
I mean, part of me,
I thought it would

00:06:25.923 --> 00:06:31.736
be like a novelty to actually
see his thinking of some

00:06:31.736 --> 00:06:34.130
of this stuff.

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:37.680
And there was like a moment in
time where if he had really,

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:39.090
really pushed on that, maybe.

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:42.964
But honestly, I could
see stuff in the book

00:06:42.964 --> 00:06:45.380
where it's like, oh, he had a
turkey sandwich on this day.

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:47.955
And then it would be five
pages about why he could not

00:06:47.955 --> 00:06:49.080
have had a turkey sandwich.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.700
And it had to be a ham
sandwich because he--

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:54.087
And it was just
going to be a mess.

00:06:54.087 --> 00:06:55.170
MALE SPEAKER: Fair enough.

00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:56.660
So how does this
conversation end?

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:57.576
You get what you want.

00:06:57.576 --> 00:06:58.650
How does it end?

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:00.080
ASHLEE VANCE:
Well, it was weird.

00:07:00.080 --> 00:07:01.230
I mean, the dinner went on.

00:07:01.230 --> 00:07:03.310
I feel like that first one
was like two or three hours.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:04.720
And it was all over the place.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:08.370
We walked about Larry
Page a bit and AI.

00:07:08.370 --> 00:07:10.300
And then we had
these other things.

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:11.890
It was very Elon.

00:07:11.890 --> 00:07:13.980
He's kind of like, I'm
looking for a PR person.

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:18.440
And they'd say, who's the
best PR person in the world?

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.250
And the conversation went
all these different ways.

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:26.240
And then, I'd thought he agreed
to participate in the book.

00:07:26.240 --> 00:07:29.400
And then right at the end,
he's kind of getting up.

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:31.210
And he stood up from
the table first.

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:34.219
And then he came back and he
put both his hands on the table.

00:07:34.219 --> 00:07:35.510
And he looked at me in the eye.

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:39.590
And then he said, do
you think I'm insane?

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:41.740
I'd already been through
this whole huge test.

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:44.360
My brain is going, is this
the last sort of riddle?

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:45.610
What does that mean?

00:07:45.610 --> 00:07:48.240
How am I supposed to
answer this question?

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:50.730
Is this the final test to
see if he'll cooperate?

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:54.460
And I remember all this stuff
was going through my brain

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:57.540
so fast while he's still
looking at you in the eyes.

00:07:57.540 --> 00:07:59.580
And I think I just
mumbled out something

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:05.570
about-- it was like, no, I mean,
I don't think you're crazy.

00:08:05.570 --> 00:08:08.230
I think some of the stuff you
do could be perceived that way.

00:08:08.230 --> 00:08:11.864
But no, I mean, I'm like
at least into the companies

00:08:11.864 --> 00:08:13.030
or I wouldn't be doing this.

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:16.825
But ultimately I
came to just think--

00:08:16.825 --> 00:08:18.960
I don't think anything I
said would have mattered.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:22.790
I think he was having
this one last gut

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:26.517
check of whether I could
be at least quasi trusted.

00:08:26.517 --> 00:08:27.600
MALE SPEAKER: Trusted, OK.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.439
So if you said yes,
I think you're crazy,

00:08:29.439 --> 00:08:30.730
you think he still would have--

00:08:30.730 --> 00:08:31.350
ASHLEE VANCE:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:32.850
I think it was a
looking into my eye

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:35.480
to sort of see what happened.

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:38.030
Or maybe, I also thought
he'd already made up his mind

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:42.096
and he was just asking
himself a little bit.

00:08:42.096 --> 00:08:42.929
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:43.909
I understand.

00:08:43.909 --> 00:08:45.240
So what was the process like?

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:46.710
You mentioned about eight
months, once a month,

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:47.540
you get together.

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:50.490
What is it like to spend
a few hours a month

00:08:50.490 --> 00:08:52.200
interviewing Elon Musk?

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:54.740
ASHLEE VANCE: It was really fun.

00:08:54.740 --> 00:08:57.065
At the beginning, it was
nerve-wracking because I never

00:08:57.065 --> 00:08:58.440
knew how many of
these interviews

00:08:58.440 --> 00:08:59.790
I would actually get.

00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:01.720
Even though he had
agreed to it, I always

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:05.685
figured that he
might do one and they

00:09:05.685 --> 00:09:07.330
he'd be like, OK, that's enough.

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:10.890
And then I thought he might
get sick of it after a while

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:11.740
and just cut me off.

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:16.130
So each one felt like
an accomplishment.

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:19.440
But then it was frustrating
because the first four,

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:22.200
I really didn't-- I was
getting lots of useful stuff,

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.040
but nothing that was-- I could
tell he was still holding back

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:25.540
a bit.

00:09:25.540 --> 00:09:28.074
And he was repeating
a lot of stories,

00:09:28.074 --> 00:09:31.830
if you watch Elon's
speeches and other talks,

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:34.460
that you would
have heard before.

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:36.510
And so that was frustrating.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.630
And then I'm still not
sure exactly what happened,

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.956
but around the
fourth meeting-- we

00:09:40.956 --> 00:09:42.330
used to always do
the same thing.

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:43.730
We would get there.

00:09:43.730 --> 00:09:44.620
He eats really late.

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:46.830
So it'd be like 8:30,
9 o'clock at night.

00:09:46.830 --> 00:09:50.725
And we would go a few times
'til just everybody had left.

00:09:50.725 --> 00:09:52.350
And it was kind of
one of those things.

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:54.110
There was like
hardly anybody there.

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:57.755
And he just-- it was like a
flip-- the switch flipped.

00:09:57.755 --> 00:10:03.360
I think he had really
committed to doing it.

00:10:03.360 --> 00:10:06.110
And he became much more
relaxed and easygoing.

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:09.290
But on the whole, it's
like what I looked forward

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:09.970
to every month.

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:10.720
It was really fun.

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:15.680
I mean, if you consider the
idea that he might actually

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:17.710
be the first guy on
Mars, it was weird to be

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:20.040
having dinner with this
guy over and over again,

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:22.004
and getting to ask him
whatever you wanted.

00:10:22.004 --> 00:10:23.295
MALE SPEAKER: Very interesting.

00:10:23.295 --> 00:10:25.970
So we'll talk a little bit
about his childhood upbringing

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:26.470
in a moment.

00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:28.386
But something that
stuck out for me

00:10:28.386 --> 00:10:29.760
when I was reading
the beginning,

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:31.570
you mentioned something
from his youth.

00:10:31.570 --> 00:10:34.260
I think he's in
Canada at this point.

00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:36.740
He's not even in college yet.

