00:21:36.127 --> 00:21:37.460
And Elon didn't play any sports.

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:40.582
And he was like the bookish
guy off in the corner.

00:21:40.582 --> 00:21:41.790
And then it was really funny.

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:43.430
I mean, I went back
and I interviewed--

00:21:43.430 --> 00:21:45.230
I found all these kids that
he went to grade school with.

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:46.355
And I was really surprised.

00:21:46.355 --> 00:21:48.670
I mean, two or
three of them said

00:21:48.670 --> 00:21:51.520
he was the least likely
guy that we thought

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:52.770
would do anything exceptional.

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:56.140
It wasn't that
they thought he was

00:21:56.140 --> 00:21:57.420
bad at anything or anything.

00:21:57.420 --> 00:22:00.160
It was just that he was so--
nobody thought about him.

00:22:00.160 --> 00:22:02.350
He just stayed to himself.

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:05.510
And then he had a really
horrendous relationship

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:09.090
with his father, which,
like in the book,

00:22:09.090 --> 00:22:14.270
he talks about having
this horrible childhood.

00:22:14.270 --> 00:22:16.040
He never-- it's kind
of unfulfilling.

00:22:16.040 --> 00:22:19.065
He never tells us exactly
what is dad did to him.

00:22:19.065 --> 00:22:21.550
And in my interviews
with him, there

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:23.880
were times when he'd start
to well up with tears.

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:25.390
And he would start
to talk about it.

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:26.514
And then he would shut off.

00:22:26.514 --> 00:22:28.840
And that happened
four or five times.

00:22:28.840 --> 00:22:31.810
But I think the sum total
of all this stuff was,

00:22:31.810 --> 00:22:36.470
I mean, you can just play
armchair psychologist,

00:22:36.470 --> 00:22:39.380
and it's like a guy who's
out to kind of prove

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:44.990
to the world he's special and
can get a lot of things done

00:22:44.990 --> 00:22:46.180
and deserves our attention.

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:47.500
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:22:47.500 --> 00:22:48.250
I appreciate that.

00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:50.210
I had one quote I wrote down.

00:22:50.210 --> 00:22:52.130
He says, I did not
have a good childhood.

00:22:52.130 --> 00:22:53.530
It was like misery.

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:57.400
And going off what you
just said, would you

00:22:57.400 --> 00:22:59.256
say that the chip
on his shoulder,

00:22:59.256 --> 00:23:01.230
do you think it formed
during that time?

00:23:01.230 --> 00:23:03.330
Does he still have it?

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:04.450
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:06.205
I definitely think so.

00:23:06.205 --> 00:23:08.080
There's sort of two
things going on with him.

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:09.580
He's always this
independent spirit.

00:23:14.085 --> 00:23:16.697
He used to always want to get
to America, to Silicon Valley,

00:23:16.697 --> 00:23:17.280
in particular.

00:23:17.280 --> 00:23:19.800
He'd read about this is where
technology is happening.

00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:22.550
He got a computer at a young
age and was really into it.

00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:25.800
And the second he's
17, he runs away

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:30.700
from home with $100 in his
pocket and lands in Canada.

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:33.690
And he's backpacking
around for a year.

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:37.920
And so he had sort of
an independent streak.

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:45.010
But I do think any
time you tell him no,

00:23:45.010 --> 00:23:48.530
he's going to try
to prove you wrong,

00:23:48.530 --> 00:23:50.850
that he can do something.

00:23:50.850 --> 00:23:53.530
It's so funny because
that quote you

00:23:53.530 --> 00:23:56.690
read, not only does
any time I ask him

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:58.750
sort of how he
got through really

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:01.720
tough times with the companies
or in his life-- I mean,

00:24:01.720 --> 00:24:03.220
he always talks
about his childhood.

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:06.710
His wives always talk about
his childhood being horrible,

00:24:06.710 --> 00:24:07.980
all his close friends.

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:09.510
So this is clearly
something that

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:15.490
left this scar and this
sort of need to get past it.

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:16.440
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:19.130
ASHLEE VANCE: And I do think
he has a chip on his shoulder.

00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:21.820
We talked a little bit sort
of like Michael Jordan kind

00:24:21.820 --> 00:24:23.320
of type figure.

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:26.800
I mean, I do think Elon's
cut using that mold.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:30.600
He's just relentless and
takes everything as a sleight.

00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:31.710
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:32.390
Thank you.

00:24:32.390 --> 00:24:36.710
To move on to maybe a
little happier things, what

00:24:36.710 --> 00:24:39.660
I was struck by is, just
as a lay person [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:43.010
of reading the book, you know
Elon is the guy, the Tesla guy,

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:45.360
SolarCity, SpaceX.

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:48.250
And you just think, how does one
man lead all these companies?

00:24:48.250 --> 00:24:49.400
And that's cool enough.

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:52.690
But then I'm reading about him
picking up a 350-pound sumo

00:24:52.690 --> 00:24:54.050
wrestler off the ground.

00:24:54.050 --> 00:24:57.740
I'm reading about him at his
birthday parties volunteering

00:24:57.740 --> 00:25:00.079
to have balloons placed
all over his body,

00:25:00.079 --> 00:25:02.370
especially in between his
legs, and have knife-throwers

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:03.650
throwing knives at him.

00:25:06.141 --> 00:25:08.432
ASHLEE VANCE: These investors
were not happy with that.

00:25:08.432 --> 00:25:10.140
MALE SPEAKER: Not
happy with that, right?

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:12.560
And the one that I love
most is this anecdote

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:15.390
that somebody says no
to him at his company.

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:16.430
Like, I can't do this.

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:17.960
And you're fired on the spot.

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:19.750
I'm going to take-- I don't know
if he fires him, but he says,

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.300
I'm going be CEO of
my two companies,

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:22.910
and I'm going to
be CEO of your job.

00:25:22.910 --> 00:25:24.307
And I'm going to
accomplish this.

00:25:24.307 --> 00:25:25.640
And he has a streak of doing it.

00:25:25.640 --> 00:25:27.170
And it always works out.

00:25:27.170 --> 00:25:28.480
Is this the profoundly gifted?

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:32.080
Is he just like a super human,
I guess, is what I'm getting at.

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:33.497
Is he really Tony Stark?

00:25:33.497 --> 00:25:35.830
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah, I mean,
I don't-- It's kind of weird

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:38.340
because it sounds like such
a fan boy kind of thing.

00:25:38.340 --> 00:25:41.660
I mean, and I tried to have
the book be really balanced.

00:25:41.660 --> 00:25:46.560
But it definitely
seems like he has--

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:51.250
He's got a stamina and a
resolve that other people, just

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:52.950
in my experience,
do not seem to have.

00:25:52.950 --> 00:25:55.010
And it's an intensity of will.

00:26:00.340 --> 00:26:02.360
And I thought this was total BS.

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:04.530
Because I'd heard these
stories about you go to him

00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:06.030
and you say this
thing's impossible,

00:26:06.030 --> 00:26:07.840
and then he does it.

00:26:07.840 --> 00:26:09.400
I mean, it just
sounds like total BS.

00:26:12.330 --> 00:26:14.110
Especially at
SpaceX, I interviewed

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:16.560
hundreds of people
that worked at SpaceX.

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:19.990
And many people said they
saw this exact thing happen.

00:26:19.990 --> 00:26:22.150
It was like you tell him
this thing can't be done

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:24.250
and he takes over the project.

00:26:24.250 --> 00:26:25.250
And he does it.

00:26:25.250 --> 00:26:27.330
And then if he does
it, you're pretty much

00:26:27.330 --> 00:26:30.590
fired at the end of that because
you said it couldn't be done.

00:26:30.590 --> 00:26:34.730
And I think it
takes a toll on him.

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:36.810
When we would be at
dinner, he would sometimes

00:26:36.810 --> 00:26:40.410
come in and just have
this really haggard look,

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:43.419
like somebody at the
end of the marathon.

00:26:43.419 --> 00:26:45.460
And he's just sitting
there at 8 o'clock at night

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:48.320
and has been at
the office all day.

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:51.970
But he seems to be able to
do that for days on end.

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:53.120
It's really strange.

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:55.453
MALE SPEAKER: Actually to
bring up an interesting thing.

00:26:55.453 --> 00:26:57.400
I decided not to read a
passage from the book,

00:26:57.400 --> 00:26:59.740
it's a couple pages
long, where you talk

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:01.510
about a typical week for Elon.

00:27:01.510 --> 00:27:03.970
And there's also a nice--
somebody put together

00:27:03.970 --> 00:27:06.470
an image of all the flights
that he takes in a year,

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:07.610
he took in one year.

00:27:07.610 --> 00:27:10.500
So how does a man run
multiple companies like this?

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.281
He has five kids?

00:27:12.281 --> 00:27:14.530
ASHLEE VANCE: You know, five
boys, twins and triplets.

00:27:14.530 --> 00:27:15.880
MALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:17.655
How is it possible?

00:27:17.655 --> 00:27:19.780
We struggle with the 24
hours we're given in a day.

00:27:21.384 --> 00:27:23.550
ASHLEE VANCE: There's all
the stuff we talked about.

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:24.930
And then he has a
lot of help as well.

00:27:24.930 --> 00:27:26.140
But I mean, isn't it strange?

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:28.060
It's a totally
abnormal existence.

00:27:28.060 --> 00:27:30.040
So more or less, it
fluctuates a little bit,

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:34.410
but it's kind of Monday,
Tuesday at SpaceX,

00:27:34.410 --> 00:27:37.490
coming in up here
sort of Tuesday night.

00:27:37.490 --> 00:27:40.880
And then Wednesday,
Thursday at Tesla.

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:42.130
And then Friday back to LA.

00:27:42.130 --> 00:27:45.570
And then typically it
seemed like the weekends

00:27:45.570 --> 00:27:47.640
would be whichever
company was having

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:49.670
the most immediate disaster.

00:27:49.670 --> 00:27:55.900
And the entire time
I was doing the book,

00:27:55.900 --> 00:28:00.210
he worked like
seven days a week.

00:28:00.210 --> 00:28:03.855
And then there's a woman in
the book, Mary Beth Brown.

00:28:03.855 --> 00:28:05.810
If Elon is kind of
like Tony Stark,

00:28:05.810 --> 00:28:07.060
she would be his Pepper Potts.

00:28:07.060 --> 00:28:10.530
She was with him from Paypal on.

00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:14.540
She devoted her life to him.

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:18.710
She lived in two cities just
like he did, had no boyfriend

00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:20.470
that I could discern.

00:28:20.470 --> 00:28:22.880
She didn't ever even have
lunch or anything like that.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:25.820
And she handled his
personal affairs,

00:28:25.820 --> 00:28:27.979
like scheduling custody
with the kids, who

00:28:27.979 --> 00:28:30.270
was going to pick them up,
like basic things like that.

00:28:30.270 --> 00:28:33.030
And then business affairs,
she handled Elon's PR,

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:36.550
more or less, for the
really top-level stuff.

00:28:36.550 --> 00:28:43.110
So she was this glue that
made everything work.

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:46.270
And then he used to
have a team of nannies.

00:28:46.270 --> 00:28:48.880
They've done a little
nanny reduction lately.

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:52.110
So/ they're down
to two or three.

00:28:52.110 --> 00:28:54.870
And then when he's up
here, he's got his staying

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:56.666
at the friends and all that.

00:28:56.666 --> 00:28:58.320
Yeah, it's a totally
crazy existences.

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:04.060
His kids-- by all accounts,
he's a very good dad.

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:06.370
It's just that his kids
live a very strange life.

00:29:06.370 --> 00:29:08.730
There's one time
we're at a dinner.

00:29:08.730 --> 00:29:12.480
And he said, I just got back
from Monaco with the boys.

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:15.550
We were watching the F1 races
with the prince and princess.

00:29:15.550 --> 00:29:20.310
And then his people
would tell me--

00:29:20.310 --> 00:29:23.230
because he brings the kids
to SpaceX on the weekends.

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:26.400
So it's like they're so bored
of going to the rocket factory.

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:28.840
And they're like the
only 10-year-old boys

00:29:28.840 --> 00:29:32.625
on the planet that are bored
of going to the rocket factory.

00:29:32.625 --> 00:29:33.750
MALE SPEAKER: That's great.

00:29:33.750 --> 00:29:36.560
That's fantastic.

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:38.935
Kind of on this thread, I
remember one of his employees--

00:29:38.935 --> 00:29:40.934
I think it's a director
of one of the companies,

00:29:40.934 --> 00:29:43.940
somebody pretty high up-- said,
I would be in Europe or China

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:46.409
and send an email at 2:30
in the morning his time.

00:29:46.409 --> 00:29:48.200
Five minutes later,
I'd get an answer back.

00:29:48.200 --> 00:29:50.300
It's unbelievable to have
support on that level.

00:29:50.300 --> 00:29:54.140
So what toll does it take
on his health and his family

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:57.620
if he's up that late
working seven days a week?

00:29:57.620 --> 00:30:00.840
ASHLEE VANCE: Well, you can see
he's been married and divorced.

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:01.730
To the second wife.

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:05.190
He's married, divorced, married,
divorced, and then gotten back

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:06.090
together with again.

00:30:06.090 --> 00:30:07.656
MALE SPEAKER: I
didn't realize that.

00:30:07.656 --> 00:30:08.156
OK.

00:30:08.156 --> 00:30:09.520
OK.

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:12.800
ASHLEE VANCE: I think
it takes a-- I don't

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:15.205
think he has anything
resembling a normal life.

00:30:15.205 --> 00:30:16.830
There's another quote
in the book where

00:30:16.830 --> 00:30:18.970
he's between wives
at the moment and he

00:30:18.970 --> 00:30:23.440
says-- I was interviewing
him at his cubicle in SpaceX

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:26.160
and he's like, I
need a date again.

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:29.160
He goes, how long do you
think a woman needs a week?

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:29.930
10 hours?

00:30:29.930 --> 00:30:32.747
Is like 10 about right?

00:30:32.747 --> 00:30:34.705
MALE SPEAKER: About the
minimum would be great?

00:30:34.705 --> 00:30:35.496
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:30:35.496 --> 00:30:36.649
And then there's another.

00:30:36.649 --> 00:30:37.940
You remind me of another thing.

00:30:37.940 --> 00:30:41.390
The guy who was talking about
when he would answer emails

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:42.130
at any time.

00:30:42.130 --> 00:30:45.070
I mean, there's one
time when Elon's

00:30:45.070 --> 00:30:47.740
in bed with Tallulah
his second wife.

00:30:47.740 --> 00:30:52.320
And the team at SpaceX has
totally screwed something up.

00:30:52.320 --> 00:30:55.100
And it's 2:00 in the morning.

00:30:55.100 --> 00:30:57.616
And he doesn't want
to wake Tallulah up.

00:30:57.616 --> 00:30:58.990
And Elon really
lays into people.

00:30:58.990 --> 00:31:04.880
So he's like whisper yelling
at these guys from bed.

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:06.840
They're all huddled
around the speaker phone

00:31:06.840 --> 00:31:10.529
taking this verbal
lashing from him.

00:31:10.529 --> 00:31:11.820
MALE SPEAKER: That's fantastic.

00:31:11.820 --> 00:31:13.580
Did you get that story
from Tallulah, or--

00:31:13.580 --> 00:31:14.680
ASHLEE VANCE: That one--

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:15.480
MALE SPEAKER: --from one
of the people [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:18.940
ASHLEE VANCE: That was from
this guy, Kevin Brogan, who--

00:31:18.940 --> 00:31:21.260
yeah, he was on--
So there's also

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:24.030
this-- I don't know if this is
common to every tech company,

00:31:24.030 --> 00:31:26.070
but at Elon's
company, they always

00:31:26.070 --> 00:31:27.380
talk about the critical path.

00:31:27.380 --> 00:31:30.240
And so it's the one thing
that's blocking the companies

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:31.500
at any point in time.

00:31:31.500 --> 00:31:33.392
And so that's where
Elon puts his focus.

00:31:33.392 --> 00:31:34.850
And so I remember
Kevin was on-- he

00:31:34.850 --> 00:31:37.270
was the guy on the critical
path at that moment.

00:31:37.270 --> 00:31:40.027
And so that meant that Elon's
watching you 24 hours a day.

00:31:40.027 --> 00:31:40.860
MALE SPEAKER: I see.

00:31:40.860 --> 00:31:41.420
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:31:41.420 --> 00:31:43.430
MALE SPEAKER: I think that's a
good segue into just what is he

00:31:43.430 --> 00:31:44.430
like with employees?

00:31:44.430 --> 00:31:47.680
It seemed like there
was a general sense

00:31:47.680 --> 00:31:51.214
of admiration, but
very varied stories

00:31:51.214 --> 00:31:52.380
on either side of that line.

00:31:52.380 --> 00:31:54.930
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah,
I mean, I think

00:31:54.930 --> 00:31:57.020
Google has some of this
going for it as well

00:31:57.020 --> 00:31:59.950
and is probably among the
