00:32:46.650 --> 00:32:51.190
But there's nobody else is going
to get it done the way he is,

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:53.540
and that these
companies are the place

00:32:53.540 --> 00:32:57.180
to do the most exciting
work in those fields.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:32:59.129
It's kind of weird.

00:32:59.129 --> 00:33:00.920
The one thing that I
was struck by the most

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:07.660
is that-- at both Tesla and
SpaceX, there's among the EVPs,

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:10.800
there's a group of people
that have been there really

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:12.940
since both companies
have been founded.

00:33:12.940 --> 00:33:14.960
So they've worked
alongside Elon through

00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:20.480
thick and thin for 10 or
12 years and pretty much

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:21.700
on a daily basis.

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:25.870
And I don't think he would
consider them friends.

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:28.690
And I don't think they
would consider him friends.

00:33:28.690 --> 00:33:33.660
I think it's still there's
always this line drawn for him.

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.475
And I don't know.

00:33:36.475 --> 00:33:38.490
I found that a
little bit weird just

00:33:38.490 --> 00:33:42.000
because they have been
through-- both companies

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.400
have almost gone
bust so many times

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:46.900
and pulled off pretty
incredible feats.

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:51.050
So it feels like this
amazing bonding exercise.

00:33:51.050 --> 00:33:51.800
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:33:51.800 --> 00:33:54.897
ASHLEE VANCE: So yeah,
he's always the boss.

00:33:54.897 --> 00:33:56.230
MALE SPEAKER: I understand that.

00:33:56.230 --> 00:33:56.732
OK, cool.

00:33:56.732 --> 00:33:58.940
I want to turn it over the
audience in a moment here.

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:00.509
A couple of quick last ones.

00:34:00.509 --> 00:34:02.550
Can you tell us about the
time that Google almost

00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:03.360
acquired Tesla?

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:04.151
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:34:08.630 --> 00:34:14.780
The Model S had
come out in 2012.

00:34:14.780 --> 00:34:17.989
And it had received way
better reviews than, I think,

00:34:17.989 --> 00:34:20.300
anyone, even Elon,
would have expected.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:22.460
Even the Detroit
automotive press

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:25.199
was saying this may be
the best car ever built.

00:34:25.199 --> 00:34:27.550
And you had this
whole first adopter

00:34:27.550 --> 00:34:32.379
wave of a lot of people in
California who bought the car.

00:34:32.379 --> 00:34:34.379
We're used the early
adopters, but early adopter

00:34:34.379 --> 00:34:37.949
for something that cost
$100,000 and its door

00:34:37.949 --> 00:34:42.650
handles may or may not
work is a leap of faith.

00:34:42.650 --> 00:34:44.630
And people bought in.

00:34:44.630 --> 00:34:45.870
Their sales were fantastic.

00:34:45.870 --> 00:34:48.650
And then things
started to cool off.

00:34:48.650 --> 00:34:52.590
After you had that first wave,
there were on the Tesla forums,

00:34:52.590 --> 00:34:54.070
there were glitches
with the car,

00:34:54.070 --> 00:34:56.517
like the windshield
wipers would go weird.

00:34:56.517 --> 00:34:57.850
The door handles would go weird.

00:34:57.850 --> 00:35:01.820
The interior was not really
where a luxury car should be.

00:35:01.820 --> 00:35:03.400
And so I think a
lot of people-- you

00:35:03.400 --> 00:35:07.550
have to place orders to
get in line for the car.

00:35:07.550 --> 00:35:10.060
And so people would put
down $5,000 to get line,

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:11.880
but they were all
waiting to actually

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:15.670
convert that to a purchase
until everything got worked out.

00:35:15.670 --> 00:35:19.500
And this was a huge
problem for Tesla.

00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:21.210
Because you're
running a factory,

00:35:21.210 --> 00:35:25.570
it's burning through tons of
money if it's not being filled.

00:35:25.570 --> 00:35:29.745
And so it was
basically, I think it

00:35:29.745 --> 00:35:35.810
was the second
quarter of 2013, Elon

00:35:35.810 --> 00:35:39.342
could plot out that they're
just going to run out of money.

00:35:39.342 --> 00:35:40.800
And he was good
friends with Larry.

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:42.300
And I think he felt
like Larry would

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:46.520
sort of-- because the
mission of the company's

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:49.600
important to Elon, I think, he
felt like Larry not only would

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:51.790
be sort of like into
buying the company,

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:54.850
but would see it through more
than maybe some other guys.

00:35:54.850 --> 00:35:59.485
And so he turned to him
for this emergency bailout.

00:35:59.485 --> 00:36:01.110
But Elon still didn't
trust him enough.

00:36:01.110 --> 00:36:04.320
He wanted to remain
CEO for, I think,

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:11.940
it was five years of time
within the auspices of Google.

00:36:11.940 --> 00:36:14.630
And he wanted an
immediate guarantee

00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:17.850
for-- it's in the book,
but it's like $3 billion,

00:36:17.850 --> 00:36:21.550
I think, of money to sort of
not only see this tough time

00:36:21.550 --> 00:36:23.930
through, but advance the
factory and everything.

00:36:23.930 --> 00:36:26.780
And then this very
Elon thing happened.

00:36:26.780 --> 00:36:31.240
He basically took
everybody in the company,

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:33.690
whether you were
in HR or marketing

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:36.050
or whatever you
did-- an engineer--

00:36:36.050 --> 00:36:39.820
and he had everybody call
every single customer who

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:43.630
had placed a reservation
and try to talk them

00:36:43.630 --> 00:36:45.990
into converting it into a sale.

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:49.760
And within two weeks,
they sold so many cars,

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:53.340
that it ended up being Tesla's
first profitable quarter.

00:36:53.340 --> 00:36:55.420
And then the stock
price immediately,

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:57.240
once they announced
that, it shot up.

00:36:57.240 --> 00:36:59.960
And then it became the best
performing stock of 2013.

00:36:59.960 --> 00:37:01.840
And so there was
never-- not only

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:05.350
did they have enough money
to see through the quarter,

00:37:05.350 --> 00:37:07.120
then Tesla became
so expensive that it

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:09.570
was like-- I don't
even think Google

00:37:09.570 --> 00:37:10.907
would've bought it anyway.

00:37:10.907 --> 00:37:12.240
MALE SPEAKER: Understandably so.

00:37:12.240 --> 00:37:13.690
Tesla almost an
Alphabet company.

00:37:13.690 --> 00:37:14.481
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:37:14.481 --> 00:37:20.912
I mean, it's a little tricky
because some of the stuff

00:37:20.912 --> 00:37:23.370
was sourced in the book, so
there's only so much I can say,

00:37:23.370 --> 00:37:26.104
but this was very
close to happening.

00:37:26.104 --> 00:37:26.870
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:37:26.870 --> 00:37:27.590
Fair enough.

00:37:27.590 --> 00:37:28.384
Very interesting.

00:37:28.384 --> 00:37:30.550
