The hyper loop was,
essentially, his version

00:44:16.164 --> 00:44:17.580
of a back-of-the-envelope
drawing.

00:44:17.580 --> 00:44:20.360
I mean, gigantic white paper,
but it's a back-of-the-envelope

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:21.910
drawing.

00:44:21.910 --> 00:44:23.947
And you see a lot of
people comparing that.

00:44:23.947 --> 00:44:25.530
And I think his idea
was to compare it

00:44:25.530 --> 00:44:27.238
against California
high speed rail, which

00:44:27.238 --> 00:44:28.910
is this gigantic
thing which used

00:44:28.910 --> 00:44:33.060
to be emblematic
of our inability

00:44:33.060 --> 00:44:35.210
as a civilization to really
accomplish big things.

00:44:35.210 --> 00:44:37.860
And his shtick is trying
to accomplish big things.

00:44:37.860 --> 00:44:39.337
To what extent do
you do you think

00:44:39.337 --> 00:44:41.170
that he's responding
to that, or that that's

00:44:41.170 --> 00:44:44.349
why he seems to be so
important, that sort of thing?

00:44:44.349 --> 00:44:46.140
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah, I
think you're spot on.

00:44:46.140 --> 00:44:47.930
I mean, I broke the
story on the hyper loop.

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:50.200
And I sat Elon the first
time he ever talked about it.

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:52.410
And it was exactly
what you said.

00:44:52.410 --> 00:44:55.440
I mean, it was
basically a brainstorm--

00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:58.460
He saw the California
high speed rail coming

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:03.110
and thought it was so disastrous
and such a horrible mistake

00:45:03.110 --> 00:45:06.630
that he had to come up
with some other proposal.

00:45:06.630 --> 00:45:08.640
I don't think-- I
know for a fact,

00:45:08.640 --> 00:45:11.940
he had no intention of building
the hyper loop initially

00:45:11.940 --> 00:45:14.090
at all, and sort of--
well, it was more

00:45:14.090 --> 00:45:20.100
like a thought exercise
and just to make people

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:23.830
see how bad the train
was and that we should

00:45:23.830 --> 00:45:26.180
be striving for something else.

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:33.100
I think Elon,
Larry, Jeff Bezos--

00:45:33.100 --> 00:45:36.510
they're all sort of
examples of people

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:40.110
who have amassed enough
wealth now to do things

00:45:40.110 --> 00:45:48.870
that governments used to do and
that are proving that they can

00:45:48.870 --> 00:45:50.970
accomplish stuff on that scale.

00:45:50.970 --> 00:45:54.020
And there doesn't seem to be a
willingness on the government

00:45:54.020 --> 00:45:56.610
side to tackle a
lot of these things.

00:45:56.610 --> 00:46:01.830
And so I guess it depends
where you are on the spectrum.

00:46:01.830 --> 00:46:04.360
If you think this is a
bunch of "Star Trek" fans

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:07.920
who have made too much
and are charging around,

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:10.440
going after these wild dreams,
or if you buy into the idea

00:46:10.440 --> 00:46:13.020
that this is the direction
we should head in.

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:18.430
I mean, I think,
if nothing else,

00:46:18.430 --> 00:46:23.140
Elon's set a good example
for believing in the spirit.

00:46:23.140 --> 00:46:26.660
Even if you just take SpaceX,
you drop the Mars thing and all

00:46:26.660 --> 00:46:30.410
that, the US used to have like
100% of the launch market.

00:46:30.410 --> 00:46:32.070
Then we went down to 0%.

00:46:32.070 --> 00:46:35.260
And we're completely
uncompetitive

00:46:35.260 --> 00:46:36.300
on the worldwide stage.

00:46:36.300 --> 00:46:39.140
And now SpaceX is easily
the low-cost leader

00:46:39.140 --> 00:46:40.200
that has brought us back.

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:44.680
It's manufacturing everything
in the United States.

00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:46.720
Lockheed and Boeing
buy Russian engines

00:46:46.720 --> 00:46:50.490
to send up our spy satellites,
which obviously the government

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:53.090
gave up if we're doing that.

00:46:53.090 --> 00:46:55.590
So, yeah, I mean I
completely agree.

00:46:55.590 --> 00:46:57.510
I think it's a really
interesting time

00:46:57.510 --> 00:47:01.070
to be alive when people can go
do these government-scale type

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:02.860
things.

00:47:02.860 --> 00:47:03.846
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:47:03.846 --> 00:47:04.470
Love the books.

00:47:04.470 --> 00:47:07.159
And actually, I felt
like I've been following

00:47:07.159 --> 00:47:08.700
Elon and Tesla and
SpaceX pretty well

00:47:08.700 --> 00:47:09.470
for the last several years.

00:47:09.470 --> 00:47:11.260
And I was amazed
how much I learned

00:47:11.260 --> 00:47:12.926
and how much I enjoyed
hearing this sort

00:47:12.926 --> 00:47:14.571
of oral integrated
way you've talked

00:47:14.571 --> 00:47:15.820
about how the stories went on.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:16.390
ASHLEE VANCE: Oh, thank you.

00:47:16.390 --> 00:47:17.680
AUDIENCE: That's unusual for
books about Silicon Valley

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:19.300
because normally you
feel like I'm just

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:20.280
reading what I've read before.

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:21.570
This is for the people
who live outside there.

00:47:21.570 --> 00:47:23.300
But this-- anyway-- this
really broke through.

00:47:23.300 --> 00:47:24.430
ASHLEE VANCE: Thank you.

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:27.410
AUDIENCE: My question was-- and
this is more just your own gut

00:47:27.410 --> 00:47:30.220
opinion-- a lot of the stuff
that Elon says and does,

00:47:30.220 --> 00:47:33.140
it's hard for me to tell if he's
being really savvy and cynical,

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:34.740
like some of the PR stuff.

00:47:34.740 --> 00:47:36.880
Or if it's just kind
of vanity, and he's

00:47:36.880 --> 00:47:37.990
off the cuff and whatever.

00:47:37.990 --> 00:47:40.950
A lot of the PR feels
very spontaneous,

00:47:40.950 --> 00:47:43.744
but you're not clear if he's
trying to sound that way, or--

00:47:43.744 --> 00:47:45.660
I remember when I first
saw the Tesla factory,

00:47:45.660 --> 00:47:47.910
there's this giant
Schuler press.

00:47:47.910 --> 00:47:50.260
And there was this crazy
story to get in the factory.

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:51.843
And then he made
them take it all down

00:47:51.843 --> 00:47:54.430
and paint it red because he
didn't like the way it looked.

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:54.990
Is it crazy?

00:47:54.990 --> 00:47:55.510
Or is it brilliant?

00:47:55.510 --> 00:47:56.093
Or is it both?

00:47:56.093 --> 00:47:58.140
I'm just kind of curious
how you break down

00:47:58.140 --> 00:47:59.030
those kind of
decisions he makes.

00:47:59.030 --> 00:48:00.821
ASHLEE VANCE: It's
funny that you ask that.

00:48:00.821 --> 00:48:02.610
There were times
when I would ask

00:48:02.610 --> 00:48:04.590
myself the exact same question.

00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:06.550
It's definitely-- I
think it's a mix of both.

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:11.340
There are these
almost like propaganda

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:13.470
sort of things that
he does internally,

00:48:13.470 --> 00:48:15.487
but they actually do
seem to work really well.

00:48:15.487 --> 00:48:17.320
Like when you into the
Tesla factor, I mean,

00:48:17.320 --> 00:48:20.260
it's hard not to
be enthusiastic.

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:22.970
And this is not some
dingy car factory.

00:48:22.970 --> 00:48:25.360
This is like an exciting
place making exciting cars

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:29.260
with all this huge massive
logos and the color.

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:32.530
And at SpaceX, everything
is this pristine white.

00:48:32.530 --> 00:48:33.990
You could eat off the floor.

00:48:33.990 --> 00:48:37.700
And it's like the white
counter, the white orchids,

00:48:37.700 --> 00:48:40.090
the white everything
all the way through.

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:46.110
And so he has this sort of--
that, to me, was the most

00:48:46.110 --> 00:48:48.590
sort of Steve Jobs-ian
part about him,

00:48:48.590 --> 00:48:51.090
is he pays attention
to things like that.

00:48:51.090 --> 00:48:53.240
The other-- and
then, you know, he's

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:56.570
also very good at--
he's definitely

00:48:56.570 --> 00:49:01.780
outclassing in PR
terms his peers

00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:04.890
at the aerospace companies
and the automotive companies.

00:49:04.890 --> 00:49:07.360
I feel bad for them sometimes.

00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:10.160
Elon will do a Reddit AMA.

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:13.577
And then Lockheed CEO's like,
I'm going to do a Reddit AMA.

00:49:13.577 --> 00:49:15.160
And then every
question is about Elon.

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:21.490
And then I remember Tesla was
having an event the same day

00:49:21.490 --> 00:49:22.840
Ford was having an event.

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:24.840
And there were like 50
people at the Ford thing,

00:49:24.840 --> 00:49:26.780
and there were
5,000 people lined

00:49:26.780 --> 00:49:29.410
up outside of the Tesla thing
all just because Elon tweeted

00:49:29.410 --> 00:49:32.645
about I may show something.

00:49:32.645 --> 00:49:34.187
And with Elon, you never know.

00:49:34.187 --> 00:49:35.645
Is it actually
going to be a thing?

00:49:35.645 --> 00:49:39.160
Or is it just going to be
some sort of software update

00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:42.610
that we're getting in six
months or-- you don't know.

00:49:42.610 --> 00:49:46.570
Other stuff, he's just
totally off the cuff

00:49:46.570 --> 00:49:49.720
and I think not very
good at what he's doing.

00:49:49.720 --> 00:49:54.070
But they have to sue the
Air Force to try and get

00:49:54.070 --> 00:50:00.470
the rights to bid on the launch
contracts for spy satellites.

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:03.077
It was a Friday afternoon when
they announced that lately.

00:50:03.077 --> 00:50:05.410
So any other company, if
you're going to sue potentially

00:50:05.410 --> 00:50:08.660
your largest customer,
and it's the government,

00:50:08.660 --> 00:50:10.640
you would like do
this strategically.

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:14.050
And what you do is call up
a reporter at "The New York

00:50:14.050 --> 00:50:16.030
Times" ahead of time
and be like, look,

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:18.950
I'm going to give you this-- I'm
going to leak you this story.

00:50:18.950 --> 00:50:21.510
And you would sort of
feed them your spin

00:50:21.510 --> 00:50:25.640
and hope the reporter does
a sympathetic SpaceX story.

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:29.262
And you have that on the
front page on Monday morning.

00:50:29.262 --> 00:50:31.220
I'm pretty sure what
happened was that Elon who

00:50:31.220 --> 00:50:34.010
wrote the press release
himself and finished it

00:50:34.010 --> 00:50:35.700
at 3:45 on a Friday.

00:50:35.700 --> 00:50:39.322
And then five minutes later,
issued the press release.

00:50:39.322 --> 00:50:41.930
And then all his PR people
were like, oh, crap.

00:50:41.930 --> 00:50:44.640
We're going to sue
the US government.

00:50:44.640 --> 00:50:46.610
Now let's sort of
figure out what

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:47.860
we're going to say about this.

00:50:47.860 --> 00:50:51.760
And that's, I think, probably
how that kind of thing goes.

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:53.820
And he talks about it in
the book a little bit,

00:50:53.820 --> 00:50:55.403
like the speeches
and stuff like that.

00:50:55.403 --> 00:50:57.665
He definitely does
not do the Steve Jobs,

00:50:57.665 --> 00:50:59.880
I'm rehearsing for
days beforehand.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:02.240
I mean, he just gets
up there and wings it.

00:51:02.240 --> 00:51:06.340
And sometimes it works,
and sometimes it doesn't.

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:09.490
You definitely have to
give him credit for being

00:51:09.490 --> 00:51:10.740
the five-tooled player.

00:51:10.740 --> 00:51:17.590
I mean, to be able to do some
of the engineering, marketing,

00:51:17.590 --> 00:51:23.140
business decisions, the
fact that he actually has

00:51:23.140 --> 00:51:26.840
a hand in all that stuff
and can do it competently

00:51:26.840 --> 00:51:28.930
if not sort of
excel at it at times

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:32.369
is like completely unusual.

00:51:32.369 --> 00:51:32.910
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:32.910 --> 00:51:34.451
What was the thing
that surprised you

00:51:34.451 --> 00:51:36.335
about him the most?

00:51:36.335 --> 00:51:39.880
ASHLEE VANCE: I think
just the once he

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:41.760
agreed to cooperate
with the book,

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:45.656
and then we-- it's probably
about like 18 months.

00:51:45.656 --> 00:51:47.280
I mean, we had this
weird relationship.

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:48.470
We were not friends.

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:49.970
It was like a
business relationship

00:51:49.970 --> 00:51:53.010
of some sort of where I was
obviously on the begging end.

00:51:53.010 --> 00:52:02.030
And so he could be this
wonderful guy to deal with.

00:52:02.030 --> 00:52:04.430
And then he can be a very
hard guy to deal with.

00:52:04.430 --> 00:52:10.406
And the ups and downs and the
intensity of that and being--

00:52:10.406 --> 00:52:11.780
I definitely am
in a weird space.

00:52:11.780 --> 00:52:13.570
I have spent way
more time with them

00:52:13.570 --> 00:52:17.409
than probably like a pretty
select group of people,

00:52:17.409 --> 00:52:19.200
especially for a
journalist, way more time.

00:52:19.200 --> 00:52:23.930
And so you would start
to hear these stories

00:52:23.930 --> 00:52:28.890
and then to get like that
up close and personal,

00:52:28.890 --> 00:52:31.800
to see the intensity of
how it operates first

00:52:31.800 --> 00:52:35.070
it was like oh OK all this
stuff makes a lot of the cell

00:52:35.070 --> 00:52:42.860
and I like I've just never met
anyone who is just all in about

00:52:42.860 --> 00:52:44.990
every single thing he does.

00:52:44.990 --> 00:52:49.800
And it just felt when everything
was finally all said and done

00:52:49.800 --> 00:52:52.780
and the book came out, it
just felt such a relief

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:57.680
because it had just
been this crazy process.

00:52:57.680 --> 00:53:00.140
And I mean, I feel
in retrospect,

00:53:00.140 --> 00:53:04.760
I really feel blessed
to have sort of gotten

00:53:04.760 --> 00:53:07.922
to know kind of what it's like.

00:53:07.922 --> 00:53:08.880
And then, I don't know.

00:53:08.880 --> 00:53:10.450
And then you hear all these
stories along that way.

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:11.740
And you're like, there's
no way this could be true.

00:53:11.740 --> 00:53:14.200
And then it turns out,
I mean, most of them

00:53:14.200 --> 00:53:18.180
seem like they are kind of true.

00:53:18.180 --> 00:53:22.010
Just sort of the
larger-than-life kind of thing.

00:53:22.010 --> 00:53:24.160
MALE SPEAKER: I've actually
got one more question.

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:25.196
We'll stop after that.

00:53:25.196 --> 00:53:27.820
And then, I think, you'll stick
around for a bit for some more.

00:53:27.820 --> 00:53:29.260
Forgive me, it's kind
of a rambling question.

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.010
But I've been thinking
about this since we

00:53:31.010 --> 00:53:32.740
spoke maybe a couple hours ago.

00:53:32.740 --> 00:53:35.620
And we compared Elon in
some ways to Michael Jordan.

00:53:35.620 --> 00:53:37.680
And just a quick side
thing for anybody

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:39.510
who's listening now
or watching later,

00:53:39.510 --> 00:53:41.070
highly recommend
going on YouTube

00:53:41.070 --> 00:53:44.760
and looking up the Hall of
Fame enshrinement speech

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:47.220
that Michael Jordan
gave a few years ago.

00:53:47.220 --> 00:53:47.970
I forget.

00:53:47.970 --> 00:53:50.010
It was about a
20-minute long speech.

00:53:50.010 --> 00:53:51.260
He gets up there.

00:53:51.260 --> 00:53:54.200
And he gets the longest
speech at the end.

00:53:54.200 --> 00:53:57.700
And he's going after guys like
John Stockton who he beat,

00:53:57.700 --> 00:53:59.430
defeated for years.

00:53:59.430 --> 00:54:01.760
And John Stockton goes up
there as humble, grateful.

00:54:01.760 --> 00:54:02.884
He's there with his family.

00:54:02.884 --> 00:54:03.570
He's at peace.

00:54:03.570 --> 00:54:05.590
Jordan's still taking shots.

00:54:05.590 --> 00:54:07.820
He flies in the
guy who was picked

00:54:07.820 --> 00:54:09.430
over him for the
high school team

00:54:09.430 --> 00:54:11.340
just to point him
out in the audience.

00:54:11.340 --> 00:54:13.574
I think he threw
a coach out, too.

00:54:13.574 --> 00:54:16.240
So we're making some comparisons
about this chip on the shoulder

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:19.090
that Elon may or
may not still have.

00:54:19.090 --> 00:54:20.680
But it's a two-part question.

00:54:20.680 --> 00:54:23.110
You've met with a lot
of these other CEOs.

00:54:23.110 --> 00:54:25.470
You met with Larry
for this book.

00:54:25.470 --> 00:54:28.390
Part one is how
does Elon compare

00:54:28.390 --> 00:54:31.570
to these other titans in a way?

00:54:31.570 --> 00:54:33.140
And part two, I'd
love to also ask

00:54:33.140 --> 00:54:38.050
you is, around time that speech
Jordan gave, ESPN, I think,

00:54:38.050 --> 00:54:42.430
did a cover story about how
Jordan can't sleep at night.

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:45.860
He has cowboy Westerns on his TV
that remind him of his father.

00:54:45.860 --> 00:54:49.405
And he needs them on all
night to be able to sleep.

00:54:49.405 --> 00:54:51.780
Do you worry or do you think
even his friends might worry

00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:55.970
that Elon someday
might be past is prime

00:54:55.970 --> 00:54:57.850
and still not
letting go, I guess?

00:54:57.850 --> 00:55:00.279
ASHLEE VANCE: I never
thought about that one.

00:55:00.279 --> 00:55:01.320
MALE SPEAKER: It's tough.

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:03.400
For such a-- I never
would've thought about it

00:55:03.400 --> 00:55:04.300
either until we spoke

00:55:04.300 --> 00:55:05.160
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:06.700
So remind me exactly what the--

00:55:06.700 --> 00:55:07.390
MALE SPEAKER: OK,
first question,

00:55:07.390 --> 00:55:09.780
how does he compare to his
contemporaries, his peers?

00:55:09.780 --> 00:55:12.779
They all are leaders just
filled with that drive?

00:55:12.779 --> 00:55:13.570
ASHLEE VANCE: Yeah.

00:55:16.590 --> 00:55:18.090
Say Elon is unique
in a couple ways.

00:55:18.090 --> 00:55:21.902
I mean, one, he
is-- to his credit,

00:55:21.902 --> 00:55:23.610
I mean, despite all
this stuff I've said,

00:55:23.610 --> 00:55:27.694
I mean, he's surprisingly down
to earth in many, many ways.

00:55:27.694 --> 00:55:28.860
I talk about it in the book.

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:30.276
When he comes into
the restaurant,

00:55:30.276 --> 00:55:33.470
he's not I'm Elon coming
in the restaurant.

00:55:33.470 --> 00:55:35.470
It's just kind of like,
I'm walking to my table.

00:55:35.470 --> 00:55:38.620
He doesn't really expect
anyone to kind of notice him.

00:55:38.620 --> 00:55:40.300
Or he just doesn't care.

00:55:40.300 --> 00:55:45.110
And he never had
lots of handlers

00:55:45.110 --> 00:55:47.690
or it was always just--
Elon was just, deal with me.

00:55:47.690 --> 00:55:48.660
Let's just do this.

00:55:48.660 --> 00:55:54.322
And he was very earnest
and authentic when

00:55:54.322 --> 00:55:56.280
he was answering questions,
or at least putting

00:55:56.280 --> 00:55:59.640
a good effort forward.

00:55:59.640 --> 00:56:02.410
And then sort of the
180 part of that,

00:56:02.410 --> 00:56:05.700
though, is that intensity thing
we were talking about before.

00:56:05.700 --> 00:56:11.470
I mean, he is on a-- I think
I've met most of the major tech

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:12.050
CEOs.

00:56:12.050 --> 00:56:17.204
And he's just like-- he's
just on a level of intensity

00:56:17.204 --> 00:56:18.120
beyond them, you know?

00:56:18.120 --> 00:56:22.630
I would say like the
Michael Jordan thing

00:56:22.630 --> 00:56:24.660
where we talked about it before.

00:56:24.660 --> 00:56:27.737
I mean, definitely does
not take no for an answer

00:56:27.737 --> 00:56:29.320
on a level that's
kind of frightening.

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:32.969
And then is just relentless.

00:56:32.969 --> 00:56:35.260
There's a guy in the book
who says something about Elon

00:56:35.260 --> 00:56:39.700
will out-think you, out-hustle,
and there's one other part.

00:56:39.700 --> 00:56:41.490
But it's always the hustle part.

00:56:41.490 --> 00:56:44.680
He will do anything to win.

00:56:44.680 --> 00:56:47.840
When we were talking about
Lockheed and the other CEOs,

00:56:47.840 --> 00:56:50.530
that's the other part where
I feel sorry for them.

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:52.219
You're just a guy
who's in a job.

00:56:52.219 --> 00:56:54.010
And you're trying to
run this company well.

00:56:54.010 --> 00:56:57.570
And there's this maniac who's
like, I'm going to destroy you.

00:57:00.450 --> 00:57:01.910
For him, it's war, right?

00:57:01.910 --> 00:57:06.400
And for these other guys, you're
a CEO running a major company.

00:57:06.400 --> 00:57:09.200
That's perfectly acceptable.

00:57:09.200 --> 00:57:10.840
And so, yeah, I
think for him, it's

00:57:10.840 --> 00:57:13.027
like everything is
a bit of a battle.

00:57:13.027 --> 00:57:13.860
